{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17588788","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17588788"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T09:10:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T09:10:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15172"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15172","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15172"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.1,0.15,0.15,0.4]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7863"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116396"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7863","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7863"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15172"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98394"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"},{"type":"tags","id":"8137"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19167"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19170"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22041"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116396","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116396"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EBarrett\u0027s oesophagus is a term used to describe the changes in the oesophagus that can occur after longstanding exposure of the oesophagus to the refluxate of gastroesophageal reflux disease (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"With regards to Barrett\u0027s, which one of the following is correct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["It is a risk factor for the development of squamous cell carcinoma","The condition will not regress","The diagnosis is based on the presence of dysplastic changes","The more confluent the areas of change, the greater the risk of malignancy","The presence of intestinal metaplasia in columnar epithelium above the gastro-oesophageal junction confirms the diagnosis"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBarrett\u0027s oesophagus is defined by the presence of \u003Cstrong\u003Eintestinal metaplasia in columnar epithelium above the gastro-oesophageal junction\u003C/strong\u003E. The diagnosis requires both endoscopic visualisation of columnar mucosa extending into the oesophagus and histological confirmation of intestinal metaplasia with goblet cells. \u003Cstrong\u003EDysplastic changes\u003C/strong\u003E may develop but are not required for initial diagnosis. The presence of goblet cells is essential for diagnosis as they confirm intestinal metaplasia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBarrett\u0027s oesophagus is a major risk factor for oesophageal adenocarcinoma, with risk increasing proportionally to the length of the Barrett\u0027s segment. The greater the length of Barrett\u0027s, the greater the risk for malignant change. The \u003Cstrong\u003Edegree of confluence\u003C/strong\u003E does not affect this. The presence of Barrett\u0027e epithelium does not have any influence on the risk of \u003Cstrong\u003Esquamous cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBarrett\u0027s oesophagus can \u003Cstrong\u003Eregress\u003C/strong\u003E, either in response to intensive medical therapy or anti-reflux surgery.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Barrett\u0027s oesophagus is defined as intestinal metaplasia in the distal oesophagus above the gastro-oesophageal junction","Barrett\u0027s oesophagus is a major risk factor for oesophageal adenocarcinoma","The risk of developing adenocarcinoma increases with the length of Barrett\u0027s segment"],"references":["Stawinski PM, Dziadkowiec KN, Kuo LA, Echavarria J, Saligram S. Barrett\u0027s Esophagus: An Updated Review. Diagnostics (Basel). 2023 Jan 16;13(2):321. doi: 10.3390/diagnostics13020321. PMID: 36673131; PMCID: PMC9858189.","Sharma P. Barrett Esophagus: A Review. JAMA. 2022 Aug 16;328(7):663-671. doi: 10.1001/jama.2022.13298. PMID: 35972481.","Khieu M, Mukherjee S. Barrett Esophagus. [Updated 2024 Sep 2]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK430979/","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98394"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15172"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21258"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21258","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21258"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/5oylkOAI0UZzN4CWNPiCBMaOMGsE8R.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/5oylkOAI0UZzN4CWNPiCBMaOMGsE8R.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":514,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98394","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98394"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-28T20:21:35+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T20:21:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7863"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116396"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updat